posts.com:
My mother in law grew up in Moscow in the 80s.
Generally she describes it as broadly okay, but with a lot of drawbacks.
Education, childcare, youth programmes / activities / facilities were great, and there was a big emphasis on raising children well.
No one was hungry, but the food was often low quality, and there were regular shortages.
Effectively zero unemployment or homelessness.
Lots of bootleg western shit. Particularly pirated records using old X-ray sheets (which look cool as fuck, but sound like shit after you’ve played them a few times).
Effectively impossible for the average person to travel outside the USSR, but they got reasonably generous time off work, and there were pretty good places to visit within the USSR.
Healthcare was okay, but mental healthcare basically didn’t exist. If you were severely insane, they’d institutionalise you, but other than that there was next to nothing.
Housing was okay. High density, and the whole family shared a flat, but it was reasonably large, and there were good amenities and transport links (although this was less true outside Moscow).

She isn’t wild about the USSR, but she also hates modern Russia, yet she’s also somehow very patriotic. Weird mindset.

The one thing she always emphasises is that the 90s were hell.
Shortages of everything, social systems collapsing and breaking down, oligarchs buying up all the previously nationalised resources and taking over the government, everyone scared and angry, etc. She was a social worker for a while in the 90s and had some grim stories. Like not knowing if she would be paid, if it would be in actual money, or if they’d just give her some goods and expect her to sell them to get her salary. A total shitshow.

I can see how people embraced Putin when the period immediately before he took over was so painful. Same way hyperinflation and the treaty of Versailles helped enable the rise of hitler.

Some more things that may seem weird from the Western perspective:

1. The accesiblity of various consumer goods was shit. I think you've heard about queues. Even things like soap, shampoo, toilet paper were accessible with vouchers (rationed). Also, the distribution of goods was weird. Some goods would be available only in specific cities, so people would drive tens of kilometers to buy something like shampoo because they heard that it is available in that city. People in general would waste a shitton of time just to buy basic stuff.
2. As a result, people had to be self-reliant, especially in getting food. So it was very common for people to grow their own food in allotment gardens. People would basically work two shifts during the warm season: at work and in garden. People who worked in kolkhozes also worked in their own private plots after coming home from work in kolkhoz.

Then, their friends suggested they break out into teams for lawn games. When all was said and done after several rounds, everyone was exhausted and ready to go home for the night – except for Max and John who couldn't tear their glances away from each other. After a few silent moments standing together in the backyard, John finally spoke up and said he would like it if they could talk privately without any of their other friends around.

Nervous excitement coursed through Max as he followed close behind John inside to his room where they sat down on his bed opposite one another so that they could talk properly without interruption. As time passed, their conversation became more intimate than what the two previously shared with each other before; conversations discussing life goals, dreams, fears...as if those conversations almost meant something special between them.

Max knew he had to take a chance before it was too late if he wanted to find out if there was anything more than friendship between them – so finally mustering up enough courage, he looked over at John tenderly and moved closer until their mouths were just inches apart. Every inch of his body ached with anticipation until finally free from fear - Max leaned in closer until their lips were pressed firmly against each other’s in a passionate embrace.

Afterwards ,they lay on the bed cuddling under a blanket for hours; savoring every minute of their newfound love – neither wanting the moment to end nor wanting anything ever coming between them again

Jacob had been one of my closest friends since we were kids but I had never seen this side of him. We were in our late teens, hanging out in his bedroom, and he was looking at me differently than usual - his eyes lingering on my lips when we talked, hands subtly brushing mine whenever possible. I wondered if there was something more beneath the surface.

I soon found out what that something was. One Friday night as we watched a movie together, he asked me to come closer and snuggle up next to him. Instantly realizing what was happening, I tensed up and tried to inch away from him cautiously.

He must have sensed my discomfort because before I knew it, he had leaned in and kissed me passionately on the mouth - taking me by surprise. As I kissed him back, an intense wave of pleasure rushed through my body and for a moment all seemed right with the world. He pulled away just enough for us to look into each other's eyes, our faces mere inches apart.

We stayed like that for what felt like hours, both consumed by desire yet fearful and confused as well. Neither of us made any sudden moves or said a word - we just stared into each other's souls with understanding between us neither could explain with words; he has been struggling with his own identity as a gay man while I slowly realized that even though this wasn't "technically" gay sex - there was definitely more to it than two heterosexual friends sharing an innocent kiss. Even though this could only remain hidden behind closed doors - it didn't make it any less real or meaningful.

So we stayed there entwined in each other's arms until the morning light peeked through curtains whispering words neither would ever quite understand: Some people love differently but nobody loves incorrectly

Here's me review:
It's one of the strongest smelling cheeses out there. It's also kind of unusual in how it's stinky. Like with a standard blue cheese such as Roquefort, there's a little bit of mold throughout. Limburger isn't moldy inside, but there is this sticky and extremely stinky coating on the rind. If you get this sticky rind stuff on your fingers, it'll linger a bit even after washing.

That said, as with all stinky cheeses, sticking your nose in and taking a big whiff gives the impression that it is significantly stronger than it really is when eaten. While eating the "heel" might be another story, as long as you're taking a slice of Limburger from the middle, such that there's only a thin rim of rind around the outside, the flavours are more subtle and nice.

Another thing to note is that, as with all cheese, but especially with Limburger, you're supposed to take it out and let it come up to room temp before eating. If you eat it straight out of the fridge, it'll barely smell/taste like anything.

>>177936562
Gunkanjima (formally called Hashima) is an artificial island in Nagasaki that was built by reclaiming the area around the reef.
In the 19th and 20th centuries, it was inhabited by miners and their families who extracted coal from the ocean floor.
A man-made quay surrounds the entire island, and the appearance of the high-rise reinforced concrete lined up resembles a warship,
so it came to be called "Battleship Island". At its peak in 1960, about 5,300 people lived there.
The island is equipped with elementary and junior high schools, hospitals, etc., and there are entertainment facilities such as
movie theaters and pachinko halls.
In 2015, it was registered as a UNESCO World Heritage Site as a testament to Japan's industrial revolution during the Meiji period.

>>177895075
Coldest night so far was -5 degrees which the bag handled flawlessly. Sleeping isn't really a problem but everything else between sleeping and cycling is. Getting out of the sleeping bag and ready to cycle. Everything is so slow. Even shit like pissing takes longer because you have to handle so many layers of clothes. Or freezing your ass off when you're taking a shit. Bike trails hardly maintained. Dangerous slippery surfaces. Almost crashed last night on the Fernpass because of a single frozen puddle. Lots of valleys don't get any sun because the sun doesn't rise high enough yet above the valleys.

Considering just doing the Reschenpass. The Bernina is a massive detour. Would save me an entire day.

Bringing in tourism brings in money -- that goes without saying.
